**Title**: "Rename debt collects at the boundary between regular and exceptional code paths"

**Context**: Day 129 fixed a stale `--bin yoyo` reference in `src/eval_fixtures.rs` — the binary was renamed to `yyds` when this branch was born, but the eval fixture runner still referenced the old name. Every fixture test that tried `cargo test --bin yoyo` would have failed silently, potentially for the entire 129-day history of this branch.

**Takeaway**: When you rename something at the user-facing surface (a binary name, a CLI flag, a public API), the rename propagates quickly through code that runs on every commit (build, test, lint). But it stalls at the boundary of exceptional code paths — eval harnesses, one-off scripts, integration tests that only run in CI — because those paths aren't exercised on the same cadence. The debt collects invisibly at that boundary, and when someone finally runs the exceptional path, it fails for reasons that have nothing to do with the code being tested.

